      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i need help with this python function for my uni coding lab. the grader is super strict about the time limit and it keeps failing my submission because the complexity is too high for large inputs. can u optimize it so it passes the runtime tests? thanks.\n\n```python\ndef find_prime_factors(n):\n    factors = []\n    d = 2\n    temp = n\n    while temp > 1:\n        while temp % d == 0:\n            factors.append(d)\n            temp //= d\n        d += 1\n    return factors\n```",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The main issue with your current function is that it checks every possible divisor, which results in a time complexity of O(n). We can optimize this by only checking up to the square root of n, because a larger factor of the number would be a multiple of a smaller factor that has already been checked. Here's the optimized function:\n\n```python\nimport math\n\ndef find_prime_factors(n):\n    factors = []\n    d = 2\n    while d * d <= n:\n        while n % d == 0:\n            factors.append(d)\n            n //= d\n        d += 1\n    if n > 1:\n        factors.append(n)\n    return factors\n```\n\nThis version of the function has a time complexity of O(sqrt(n)), which is much more efficient for large inputs.",
      "source": "target",
